    "created_at": "2020-07-06T12:01:22Z",
    "updated_at": "2020-07-06T12:01:22Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "So the current state of the Rust ecosystem is that there are two kinds of error handling libraries ([1], [2]):\r\n\r\n1) Those that use a custom, crate-defined types and traits for error handling\r\n2) Those that use the newer stable incarnation of the stdlib `Error` trait\r\n\r\nOf the two, clearly (2) is the more future-proof way.  The problem is that the parts of the standard library that deal with backtraces [haven't been stabilized yet](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/53487#issuecomment-638878790), so the crates that rely on stdlib (e.g. anyhow) can't take advantage of backtraces on stable rustc yet.  Since [stdlib backtraces have been already proposed for stabilization](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/53487#issuecomment-638878790), I think the best way is to wait for a new release of anyhow that includes stable backtraces instead of buying into some (1) crate that will soon become deprecated.\r\n\r\n[1]: https://blog.yoshuawuyts.com/error-handling-survey/\r\n[2]: https://nick.groenen.me/posts/rust-error-handling/",
